    "title": "Are humans the only animal whose hair or fur will grow to an arbitrary length if not cut? - Quora",
    "tags": [
        "Human Evolution"
    ],
    "response": [
        {
            "author_info": {
                "name": "Emily Altman",
                "href": "/profile/Emily-Altman"
            },
            "answer_text": "Our hair actually does not grow to arbitrary lengths.  Hair goes through a growth cycle, consisting of three phases:  Anagen, the growth phase, that lasts approximately 3 years.  In some people, called angora mutations, anagen can last up to 10 years.  That's how we get people that can seemingly grow their hair to arbitrary lengths.Catagen, a brief interim phase, that lasts approximately 3 weeks immediately after anagen stops.Telogen, a 3 month resting phase at the end of which the old hair falls out and a new hair cycle starts.The hair cycles are pretty similar in furry animals.  A number of different animals have angora mutations. The Angora Rabbit (http://www.lilopet.com/2011/09/angora-rabbit/)  ",
